-- Description --

BaSbbs is a concurrent, multithreaded bulletin board server that provides users with a series of protocols for interacting with 
the bulletin board file.

When the server starts, it reads the provided configuration file into a global struct, reads through the bbfile to obtain the 
highest message id, then begins handling clients. 

protocol.c is responsible for handing the specified application protocol and utilizes bbfile.c to carry out any required file 
manipulations. As a security feature, protocol.c implements 4kb buffers and truncates any provided input in the event of overflow.

bbfile.c ensures two threads do not write to the file at the same time, read while another is writing by utilizing the readers-writers 
paradigm defined in lock.c.

server.c handles accepting connections to clients, allocating and deallocating threads, and implementing concurrency using those threads.
The preallocation portion of this file was inspired by the code provided in mtpserv but differs where it uses the main process as a monitor 
instead of spawning a new dedicated monitor thread. Furthermore, in order to support the destruction of idle threads, a poll was introduced 
with a delay of two seconds to ensure idle threads do not remain blocked at accept, allowing them to be reaped by quickly instead of having 
to wait for additional clients to connect. In hindsight, using a queue to hold sockets may have been a more elegant solution, albeit slightly 
more complex.


-- Test Suite Follows --

Configuration:
The server prints the config variables to terminal on startup.

- The program correctly parses the provided config file values when provided in either the cwd or cli.

- The server does not accept a missing bbfile value but will create a bbfile using the name provided in the config in 
  the event such file does not exist.

- The program uses the default values in the event the optional variables are not in the config.


Application Protocol:

Client Handling
  - Upon connecting to the server through telnet localhost, the server sends the correct connection message.
  - When no USER name is provided, the client defaults to Anonymous Coward.

USER connection
  - "USER" -> server sends "Usage: USER name".
  - "USER Dennis Ritchie" -> server sends appropriate 1.0 message.
  - "USER Ken/Thompson" -> server sends appropriate 1.2 message.

WRITE operations
  - "WRITE" -> "Usage: WRITE message".
  - "WRITE Architect of the greatest programming language" -> responds "3.0 WROTE 1".
  - "READ 1" -> outputs "2.0 MESSAGE 1 Dennis Ritchie/Architect of the greatest programming language".

USER switching and WRITE
  - "USER Ken Thompson" -> "1.0 HELLO Ken Thompson greetings".
  - "WRITE And the Unix operating system!".
  - "READ 2" -> "2.0 MESSAGE 2 Ken Thompson/And the Unix Operating System!".
  - "READ 3" -> "2.1 UNKNOWN 3 Could not find message on file".

REPLACE
  - "REPLACE" -> "Usage: REPLACE message-number/message".
  - "REPLACE 1 This should replace the first write" -> "4.0 REPLACED 1".
  - "READ 1" -> "2.0 MESSAGE 1 Ken Thompson/This should replace the first write".

QUIT
  - "QUIT" -> "9.0 BYE Goodbye, Connection closed by foreign host."


Bulletin Board:
In order to test the readers-writers paradigm, FDEBUG has been set to true/1 in the config in the following section. These delays can be seen in the program
terminal.

- The server is stopped, started again on the same file, and a new WRITE is entered, the write operation occurs on the current highest id + 1.

- when a WRITE operation is carried out in one telnet session and a read operation is carried out in another, the read only completes once the 
  WRITE has finished. The same behavior occurs when the REPLACE command is used instead of WRITE. This proves the file cannot be read by one thread 
  when another thread is writing to the file.

- When two READ operations occur between threads, both finish at the same time, proving multiple read operations can occur on the file simultaneously.

- When a new, clean bbfile is provided, the first WRITE occurs at ID 1. When the previous bbfile is introduced back on restart, the ID begins from 
  that files specific highest ID.


Multithreading:
The following testing has been completed with Thincr set to 5 and Thmax set to 6.

- Using the "ps" command, five plus one thread (main process) are shown to exist. This is the correct number of threads that should 
  be preallocated at the start.

- Connecting five telnet clients to the server spawns an additional five threads for a total thread pool of ten. This is the correct 
  behavior when all threads are active, allowing for increased traffic up to the maximum.

- Connecting two additional telnet clients does not spawn additional clients. This aligns with the "at most Tincr + Tmax threads" requirement.

- When eight telnet clients are connected to the server and five QUIT, 5 of the idle threads are quit. This aligns with the "less than 𝑛 − Tincr − 1 threads, 
  kill tincr idle threads".

- When more clients than the maximum number of allowed clients (10 in this case) try to connect, they get stuck waiting until a free slot opens up. This is 
  correct.

- When all the active clients QUIT, all additional preallocated threads are removed from the pool but tincr threads remain idle.


